aws-transcripts.transcript: I'm gonna talk about the power of a word. You're hot. Tow the vast majority off practicing Muslims. Jihad is an internal struggle for the faith. It is a struggle within struggle against vice sin, temptation, lost greed is that struggle to try and live a life that is set by the moral cords written in the Koran. In that original idea, the concept of jihad is as important to Muslims as the idea off grace is to Christians. It's a very powerful words. If you look at it in that respect and there's a there's a certain, almost mystical resonance toe. And that's the reason why, for hundreds of years, Muslims everywhere have named their children their daughters as much as their sons in the same way that, say, Christians named their daughters Grace and Hindus. My people Neymar daughters Bhakti, which means in Sanskrit, spiritually worship. But they've always been in Islam, a small group of minority who believe that jihad is not only an internal struggle but also an external struggle against forces that would threaten the faith or the faithful. And some of these people believe that in that struggle, it is sometimes OK to take up art. And so the thousands of young Muslim men who flocked to Afghanistan in the 19 eighties to fight against the Soviet occupation of a Muslim country. In their minds, they were fighting a jihad. They were doing jihad, and they named themselves the Mujahideen, which is a word that comes from the same root jihad. And we forget this now. But back then, the mujahideen was celebrated in this country. In America. We thought of them as as holy warriors who were taking the good fight to the ungodly communist America gave them weapons, gave them money, gave them support, encourage. But within that group, a tiny small group of minority within a minority within a minority, we're coming up with new, dangerous conception of job. And in time this group would come to be led by Osama bin Laden, and he refined the idea. His idea of jihad was a global war on terror, primarily targeted at the far enemy of the Crusaders from the West against America. And the things he did in the pursuit of this jihad was so horrendous, so monstrous, and had such great impact that his definition was the one that stuck not just here in the West. We didn't know any better. We didn't suppose toe ask. We just assumed that if this insane man and his psychopathic followers were calling, what they did jihad, and that's what jihad must mean. But it wasn't just us. Even in the Muslim world, his definition of jihad began to gain acceptance. A year ago I was in Tunis and I met the the mama for a very small mosque and old man. 15 years ago, he named his granddaughter Jihad after the old meaning. He hoped that a name like that would inspire her to live a spiritual life. But he told me that after 9 11 he began to have second thoughts.
